title: Boulder Junior Cycling  MTN Training Ride
Colorado Springs MTB Skills Camp
description:
The Colorado Springs MTB Skills Clinic will teach riders from beginner to intermediate the core skills necessary to enhance safety, fun, and learning on the MTB. Riders will start with a morning session of fundamental movements that are required for continued MTB success. Skills include, but are not limited to: straight line drills, bunny hopping progression, intro to cornering, and understanding switchbacks. 

Days will be complete, starting at 8am and ending at 4pm. The morning sessions will be used to develop the necessary skills on a safe surface (grass) before moving to Ute Valley Park to do a skills ride on variable terrain. 

A bonus to this clinic will be the ability of riders to get a pre-ride of the \"Ute Valley Pro XCT\" MTB course before race day. Riders will be able to come into that race feeling more confident and ready to succeed!
course: Pinon Valley Park and Ute Valley Park in Colorado Springs will both be used for the skills clinic. Pinon Valley Park provides a large grass field for skill progressions in a safe and fun learning environment, while Ute Valley Park has something to challenge every rider.
registration:
Registration cost is $99 for 1 1/2 days. This includes Saturday morning, Saturday afternoon, and Sunday morning. 

Registration fee does not include food or fluid. Lunch is on your own, but with plenty of choices within riding and driving distance, a group lunch will be likely. 

Riders must possess a current and valid USAC racing license before the day of the clinic. For riders who do not have a license, one-day licenses can be purchased for $5 per day. Registration is completed on-line through USA Cycling.
notes:
If there are specific areas of skill development you would like to focus on, please email Ryan Kohler at ryankohler@wenzelcoaching.com before the event and we will do our best to accommodate your needs. 

Please arrive ready to ride with: 
* extra tubes, repair kit, pump or CO2, etc
* fluid, food, pack for 3-4 hours of outdoor exposure
* sunscreen
* USAC racing license (unless using 1-day license)
directions:
Pinon Valley Park and Ute Valley Park are both located at 
5585 Mule Deer Drive in Colorado Springs, Colorado. From I-25, take the Garden of the Gods Exit (#146) and travel West on Garden of the Gods Road until you reach Centennial Blvd. Go North (right) on Centennial for 1.5 miles before turning East (right) onto Mule Deer Drive. 

Parking is available along Mule Deer Drive and on Pinon Park Drive. The clinic will meet under the covered picnic area near the southwest portion of the park.

title: MSC #1, RIVERSIDE RAMPAGE
description:
The second annual Riverside Rampage mountain bike race is set for May 18-20 in Salida, Colo. Two days of racing with three different stages are planned for the weekend. Registration and packet pick-up will be at the Boathouse Cantina located at 228 north F Street in historic downtown Salida, Colo.

The weekends events include a two-mile hill climb time trial up Tenderfoot Mountain (a.k.a. S Mountain) Saturday morning. Afterward well be racing a lengthened version of short track on Tenderfoot Mountain. Sunday will be the cross-country race on the Arkansas Valley Hill Trails on and behind Tenderfoot Mountain.

You may enter all the events or pick and choose the events that best suit your racing style. For riders who participate in all three events there will be an overall award for those riders including a fourth set of points towards their Mountain States Cup Series overall standings.

description: The Steamboat Stinger is a 50 mile epic mountain bike race taking place in Steamboat Springs, CO. You can either race all 50 miles solo, or as a duo team, one 25 mile lap each.
course: You can expect singletracklots of it. Beginning at the Howelson Hill Ski Area right in the heart of Steamboat, the course takes an extended detour deep into the beautiful backcountry of Routt County before returning to the transition/finish area. Racers will wind through open meadows, deeply-cupped, aspen-lined, narrow Colorado loam and wild sage gardens offering incredible views of the surrounding peaks and valleys. It\'s a 50-mile race composed of two 25-mile loops - 100% of which are on dirt featuring 90% singletrack.

description: Theres a new SPIN on Rock n Roll for 2012:  the Rock n Roll Denver Marathon &  Marathon benefiting the Prostate Cancer Foundation will offer a bike tour as part of the race weekend lineup!  The non-timed Rock n Roll Denver Bike Tour will cover nearly 24 miles of the marathon course and take place prior to the full and half marathon on Saturday, September 22. Dont miss out on this opportunity to tour Denver on closed streets before the big race.
course:
Race Day Schedule:*

    Date: Saturday, September 22, 2012
    Time:  6:45 am  Bike Tour Start (7:15 am - Marathon, half marathon & Relay Wave Start)
    Location:  Civic Center Park-  Start: Broadway and Colfax Ave./ Finish: Bannock St. and 14thAve.
registration:
Numbers:
	Participant Perks:
Limited to: 750 cyclists

Bike Tour Fees*

    $60 (through 9/16/12 or sell out)

	

    Unique opportunity to ride the streets of Denver before the race
    24-mile bike ride of the existing marathon course
    Official Participant T-shirt
    Swag Bag
    Official Finishers Medal
    Entertainment on the Course
    Finish Line Festival with one FREE beer courtesy of Michelob Ultra**

Continue Registration 
 
Registration Notes:

    *Registration fees are non-refundable and non-transferable. Fees listed above do not include the RaceIt processing fee. There is NO RACE DAY REGISTRATION.
    If you have registered for the full or half marathon and now want to participate in the bike tour, you will have to register for the bike tour separately. You will not receive a refund for the full/half marathon.
    Registration is only available online, and closes Sunday, September 16, 2012 (11:59 pm PST) or earlier upon sell out.
    **Important note: State law requires your photo ID to be checked on race day, even if youre 99! Plan ahead and have your photo ID with you.
notes:
Event Details

    The age minimum for the Rock n Roll Bike Tour is 12 years old.
    Bike tour is non-timed and non-competitive: Top speed limited to 20 MPH (3 minute miles).
    Minimum speed is 10 MPH (6 minute miles)
    On course technical support
    No fixed-gear bikes (brakes required)
    Single-rider bikes only
    No trailers, tandems, tricycles or training wheels
    Helmets required
    Self supported ride  bring your own water bottle and snacks (no sag stops). Refreshments will be provided at finish line.
    Post-race bike check will be made available at finish line
    Registrants may only participate in ONE Rock n Roll Denver event on race day.
    GEAR CHECK WILL NOT BE PROVIDED TO BIKE TOUR PARTICIPANTS. Instead, Bike Tour participants are encouraged to carry their own gear bags with them during their ride.

Event Rules

Welcome to the Inaugural Rock n Roll Denver Bike Tour! Please read these ride rules and recommendations very carefully for a safe and enjoyable event.

Please remember that this inaugural event is a non-timed, non-scored fun fitness ride on the marathon run course.  Please be extra careful and considerate of your fellow riders.

    All Entrants must line up in the official start line area- Entrants may not start in front of this area or jump into the ride along the course.
    All Entrants must properly enter the Start lineup, and may not cut in line, climb over barricades, or in any other way improperly enter the Start area;
    All Entrants must wear an approved helmet (CPSC certified);
    All Entrants must obey Police, Bike Patrol or other Event Officials including not passing the lead police or official lead cyclists.
    No Entrant may ride with, or receive support from, unregistered cyclists (bandits);
    No entrant may utilize a motorized or power-assisted bicycle nor may a bicycle have such devices attached. All bicycles must be powered solely by human force.
    All Entrants should cycle the complete official route, as described on the official route map, unless they are forced to leave the course due to mechanical issues or because they have fallen behind the official timeline. All Entrants must stay behind, and not pass, the lead vehicle;
    All Entrants must wear their rider numbers, which must be easily visible;
    Headsets covering or blocking both ears are prohibited, i.e., no iPods or other MP3 players or headphones/earbuds;
    Aero-type and other similar auxiliary handlebars are prohibited; this includes tri-bikes with otherwise unremovable aerobars.
    All Entrants must start the Event before the last official vehicle (trail vehicle) has left the start line. Because the runners are starting behind you, no late cyclists will be allowed on the course.
    Cyclists should bring their own filled water bottles and any snacks or food. Due to the relatively short distance of the ride and the time schedule for the morning, there are no SAG stops or rest stops providing fluids or food. Note that you will ride by water stations but these are set up for the runners who will be right behind the cyclists.
    Team tactics that endanger, or impede the progress of, any other cyclists, such as blocking, are prohibited;
    All Entrants must show courteous behavior to Volunteers, Event Officials, and Police, and obey their instructions;
    All Entrants must obey traffic control officers & personnel, and traffic control devices & signs, unless otherwise directed by an Official;
    Do not cross through any cone lines. Some sections of the route are two-way cyclist traffic or will have runners on one side of the road and cyclists on the others. Think safety first and stay in your correct lane at all times.
    Medical stations will be staffed along the course and at the finish line for basic first aid. Look for the red tents.
    Restrooms are located throughout the bike tour course; look for these near the band sites, runner water stations, and medical stations.
    All Entrants must read and know State bicycle laws, and must yield to emergency vehicles at all times, even if the road is closed;
    All Entrants must ride the entire event on the bicycle they start on  changing bicycles is prohibited;
    Be PredictableSmooth, consistent riding is the key to ensuring everyone riding around you feels comfortable and that you are not a hazard to yourself or anyone else
    All Entrants must verbally warn others when they overtake them  call out Passing, your left, or on your Left (the simpler, the better);
    Do NOT Overlap WheelsBe cognizant of those around you and pay attention to the position of your front wheel vs. their back wheel
    Entrants not on schedule to finish the event in the alloted timeframe will be stopped and transported to the Finish Line;
    Rule Enforcement & Procedures: 1) Police, Event Officials, and Bike Patrol will identify any Entrant who violates traffic laws or Event rules for possible disciplinary action
    SignalSignal with your hands and/or voice so that everyone knows your intentions
    Entrants are solely responsible for all their items of personal belongings. We cannot be responsible for any items of personal belongings whatsoever, whether lost, stolen, placed in our care, or misplaced.
    Tandem Bikes, child trailers, training wheels, child seats, child bike extensions, or animals are prohibited. This is for safety of all riders and runners.
    Headlights and flashing tail lights are highly recommended. The ride begins a few minutes before sunrise.
    The ride will happen rain or shine.
    Limited mechanical assistance will be provided before the race, on course, and at the finish line. Participants are highly encouraged to make sure their bike is tuned up with fresh tires and tubes. Please bring extra tubes, a patch kit, and a pump or CO2 inflation device with you during the ride.
    Unauthorized/unregistered riders are legally not covered by the event.

 
Rock n Roll Bike Tour Packet Pick-Up

    Participants must attend the Health & Fitness Expo to pick up their race number, Official Participant T-shirt and swag bag.
    You are not allowed to pickup for anyone else.
    Photo IDs and Confirmation Sheet are required.
    Race day packet pick-up is NOT available.

description: USA Cycling 24-Hour Mountain Bike National Championships
course: 13+mile course twisting through the largest city park with short climbs, tech sections, and more that 50% single track.  Weather and trails consistant with semi-arid climate in the foothills of the Rocky Mountains.  The course is designed by local mountain bike riders and is a true test of fitness and riding skill.
registration: USAC online registration is open to all participants within USA Cycling 24-Hr Nat. Championship categories.  Non-championship racers must register via the event website at www.24hoursofcos.com.  See site for more information on available racing categories.
notes: Due to the location of the race being in a city owned park, please read fully the camping rules and race rules for the event.  USAC rules of competition apply and racers are expected to abide by USAC rules, while complying with any special rules we have posted out of respect for the park.  See www.24hoursofcos.com for race specific information and consult the USAC rulebook for other competition rules.
directions: Colorado Interstate 25 to Academy Blvd.  Academy Blvd. south to Maizeland.  Turn east on Maizeland, then enter Palmer Park.

address.street: North Area Athletic Complex, 19500 West 64th Parkway

title: Fruita Fall Flyer
description: A fall mountain bike event not to miss, in Fruita, CO.  A fast and fun cross country event on Saturday with both Collegiate and Open Categories at the famous 18Rd.  Sunday morning finishes the weekend with exciting short track racing for both Collegiate and Open Categories.
course: The cross country will feature a 10.5 mile loop of fast, flowing singletrack, on the famous 18Rd trails, including Prime Cut and Chutes and Ladders.
registration: Online registration is highly encourage. On site reg is available (add $15). Collegiate racers must present a current USA Cycling collegiate license. Non Collegiate racers in cat 1 must also present an annual USA Cycling  license.  To register online you must log into your USA Cycling account or create one (free) if needed to submit your electronically signed waiver.
directions: Take I-70 to the Fruita Exit and go North.  Go straight at the light on Cherry St, until Ottley.  Right on Ottley, followed by a left on Maple (17Rd).  Take 17Rd to N 3/10 Rd where you will make a right, followed by a left on 18Rd 1 mile later.  Continue to the cattle guard, where the road turns to dirt.  After 1/4 mile, follow signs right on 18.6 Rd to event 2 miles down road.

title: USGP Cyclocross -  SmartWool Cup p/b FC Bikes
description: The second stop of the USGP Cyclocross -  SmartWool Cup p/b FC Bikes - blasts off the starting line on October 13th and 14th, 2012.   Fort Collins and Colorado is home to a number of cyclocross standouts - including Olympian Georgia Gould, Meredith Miller and up and coming U23 racer Skyler Trujillo - and the battle for home town bragging rights always makes for an amazing day of racing.
course: The course is a challenging one but the viewing is easy! The course features rough grasses, mud, steep hillsides and a big blue fly-over!
registration: Online registration is available on BikeReg.com.   Registration opens at 9am eastern on August 10th, 2012 and closes on October 10th, 2012 at 10 pm eastern.  Pre-registration is MANDATORY for the Elite /UCI races.   On-site registration is available for all other categories and a $10 per day late fee will be charged.
notes: NO REFUNDS - and events are rain or shine.
directions:
The course is located at 5757 S College Ave
Fort Collins, CO 80525.

title: Mile High Urban CX Chaos
description: MUCCY will provide the only CX course in the USA geared to cyclists with adaptive equipment.  This adaptive course is dedicated to our veterans returning from the wars.   We will provide timing chips to the adaptive cyclists so they can participate as a race however the half-hour ride is open to anyone in an adaptive cycle  - we particularly encourage those that have not tried it before.  It is our goal to provide a healing, therapeutic activity.
course: The course will be the same as the Mile High Urban CX Course with some adaptive elements
registration: Registration is free to all adaptive cyclists.

title: Mile High Urban CX Chaos
description:
MILE HIGH URBAN CX CHAOS
November 11, 2012  Veterans Day

RiNO  RIVER NORTH ART DISTRICT:
RiNo is bounded by I-70 to the North, I-25 to the West, Park Avenue West to the South, and Lawrence to the East. While retaining its industrial roots, the RiNo neighborhood is now fertile ground for arts, artists and urban cyclocross racing..

MUCCY is providing the only CX Course in the USA geared to cyclists with adaptive equipment.  This adaptive course is dedicated to all of our veterans that were wounded serving our country.
course: An Urban Adventure that will consist of tires, tracks, warehouses, sand, alleys and city streets.   The map of the course will not be revealed until November 10th.
